{{short description|A Latin phrase meaning with the sun, sometimes used in meteorology and physical oceanography to refer to anticyclonic motion}} '''Cum sole''' is a Latin phrase meaning ''with the sun''. The term is sometimes used in [[meteorology]] and [[physical oceanography]] to refer to [[anticyclonic]] motion, which is [[clockwise]] in the [[Northern Hemisphere]] and [[counterclockwise]] in the [[Southern Hemisphere]] (but ''with'' the sun's apparent motion when facing [[Equator]] in both [[hemispheres of the Earth|hemispheres]]) (Pond and Pickard, 1983).<ref name=pon83>{{cite book | year=1983 | title=Introductory dynamical oceanography (2nd ed.) | author=Pond |author2=Pickard | isbn=0-7506-2496-5 | publisher=Pergamon Press | url=https://books.google.com/?id=5pQf8dBYxIUC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref>
The opposite of '''Cum sole''' is '''Contra solem''' ([[cyclonic]] motion). Both terms are infrequently used.
