{{Infobox book <!-- |italic title = (see above) --> | name = The World in Six Songs | image = The World in Six Songs.jpg <!-- include the file, px and alt: Example.jpg --> | caption = | author = [[Daniel J. Levitin]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = U.S.A. | language = English | series = | subject = music; cognitive neuroscience; anthropology;evolution; memoir | genre = | publisher = [[Dutton Books|Dutton]]/[[Penguin Books]] | pub_date = 2008 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 368 | isbn = 978-0452295483 | oclc = 757065811 | dewey = 781/.11 | congress = ML3838.L48 2008 | preceded_by = [[This Is Your Brain on Music]] | followed_by = [[The Organized Mind]] }}
'''''The World in Six Songs: How the Musical Brain Created Human Nature''''' is a [[popular science]] book written by the [[McGill University]] [[neuroscientist]] [[Daniel J. Levitin]], and first published by [[Dutton Penguin]] in the U.S. and Canada in 2008, and updated and released in paperback by Plume in 2009, and translated into six languages. Levitin’s second ''New York Times'' bestseller, following the publication of ''[[This Is Your Brain on Music]]'', received praise from a wide variety of readers including Sir [[George Martin]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Elizabeth Gilbert]], and [[Adam Gopnik]]. The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it "masterful". The ''[[New York Times]]'' wrote: "A lively, ambitious new book whose combined elements can induce feelings of enlightenment and euphoria. Will leave you awestruck."<ref name="Itzkoff">Itzkoff, D. (2008, August 31). "Book Review". ''[[The New York Times]]'', p. BR5.</ref> ''[[The Times]]'' wrote "Levitin is such an enthusiastic anthropologist, such an exuberant song and dance man, such a natural-born associative thinker, that you gotta love the guy." <ref name="Finlayson">Finlayson, I. (2009, April 18). "Book Review". ''[[The Times of London|The Times]]''</ref> It was named one of the best books of 2008 by the ''[[Boston Herald]]'' and by ''[[Seed Magazine]]''.<ref name="Seed">Seed Magazine (2008, December 23). "SeedPicks 2008". ''[[Seed Magazine]]''</ref>
''The World in Six Songs'' combines science and art to reveal how music shaped humanity across cultures and throughout history. This book leans more heavily on [[anthropology]] and [[evolutionary biology]] than did ''This Is Your Brain On Music'', which skewed more toward findings in [[psychoacoustics]] and [[neuroscience]].
Levitin identifies six fundamental song functions or types (friendship, joy, comfort, religion, knowledge, and love) then shows how each in its own way has enabled the social bonding necessary for human culture and society to evolve. He shows, in effect, how these six song types function in our brains to preserve the emotional and literal history of our lives and species. Levitin illuminates, through songs, how music has been instrumental in the evolution of language, thought and culture. Musical examples ranging from [[Beethoven]] to [[The Beatles]], [[Busta Rhymes]] to [[Bach]], are used to support the book's propositions.
Using cutting-edge scientific research from his music cognition lab at [[McGill University]]; his own experiences in the music business; and interviews with musicians such as Sting and [[David Byrne]], as well as conductors, anthropologists, and evolutionary biologists.
