'''Wolfgang Karl Weyrauch''' (1907 - 1970) was a [[Germany|German]] - [[Peru]]vian  [[Malacology|malacologist]] and [[Entomology|entomologist]].

==Life==
Wolfgang Karl Weyrauch was born on December 7, 1970, in [[Elberfeld]], Germany. He received his PhD in Zoology in 1929 from the [[University of Berlin]] with a thesis on insect neurophysiology.<ref name="Barbosa2008">{{cite journal | last1 = Barbosa | first1 = André F. | last2 = Delhey | first2 = Valdemar K. | last3 = Coan | first3 = Eugene V. | title = Molluscan Names And Malacological Contributions Of Wolfgang Karl Weyrauch (1907–1970) With A Brief Biography | journal = Malacologia | volume = 50 | issue = 1 | year = 2008 | pages = 265–277 | issn = 0076-2997 | doi = 10.4002/0076-2997-50.1.265}}</ref> From 1928 to 1929, he was an assistant of [[Richard Hesse]], and from 1931 to 1943 he worked for the German Council of Scientific Research doing field studied on entomology and ecology.<ref name="Barbosa2008" />

In 1938, he worked as an entomologist at the agricultural experimental station (Estación Agrícola de La Molina) in [[Lima]]. At the time of the [[World War II]], he moved to [[Texas]], where he did field work in entomology and malacology. In 1946, he was at the Estación experimental Agrícola de Tingo María in Lima. From 1948 on, he worked for the [[National University of San Marcos|Universidad Mayor de San Marcos]] in Lima as a Professor of zoology and Genetics at the [[Museum of Natural History, Lima|Museo Nacional de Historia]]. In addition, he was from 1959 to 1961 Professor of agricultural zoology at the [[Pontifical Catholic University of Peru|Pontificia Universidad Católica del Lima]]. In 1962, he went to Argentina and became professor at the Instituto Miguel Lillo in [[San Miguel de Tucumán|Tucumán]]. He died of a heart attack in 1970.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}

==Works==
Weyrauch studied land and freshwater gastropods of [[South America]], mainly taxa belonging to the families [[Camaenidae]], [[Charopidae]],  [[Clausiliidae]], [[Endodontidae]], [[Helicinidae]], “[[Hydrobiidae]]”, [[Orthalicidae]], [[Pupillidae]], [[Scolodontidae]], [[Subulinidae]], and [[Urocoptidae]]. He left behind many type specimens in museums, of which he published no original description. He was the author of 198 molluscan names.

==Species named in his honor==
The following gastropod species were named after Weyrauch:<ref name="Barbosa2008" />
*''[[Bostryx weyrauchi]]'' {{small|[[Henry Augustus Pilsbry|Pilsbry]], 1944}}
*''[[Neopetraeus weyrauchi]]'' {{small|Pilsbry, 1944}}
*''[[Thaumastus weyrauchi]]'' {{small|Pilsbry, 1944}}
*''[[Nenia weyrauchi]]'' {{small|Pilsbry, 1945}}
*''[[Incapora weyrauchi]]'' {{small|[[Eveline Du Bois-Reymond Marcus|Du Bois-Reymond Marcus]], 1953}}<ref name=Eveline1953>{{cite journal | last1 = Du Bois-Reymond Marcus | first1 = Eveline | authorlink1 = Eveline Du Bois-Reymond Marcus | title = Some South American triclads | journal = Anais da Academia Brasileira de Ciências | year = 1953 | volume = 25 | issue = 1 | pages = 65–78}}</ref>

Also, a species of snake is named after Weyrauch:<ref>Beolens, Bo; Watkins, Michael; Grayson, Michael (2011). ''The Eponym Dictionary of Reptiles''. Baltimore: JohnsHopkins University Press. xiii + 296 pp. {{ISBN|978-1-4214-0135-5}}. ("Weyrauch", p. 283).</ref>
*''[[Leptotyphlops weyrauchi]]'' {{small|[[Braulio Rubí Orejas-Miranda|Orejas-Miranda]], 1964}}

